      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Harvard_604760_1826-03_page01.jpg"/>
            <p>Miss Edgeworths respects to<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#NortA1">Professor Norton</persName> She returns<lb/>
                    him her sincere thanks for<lb/>
                    the honor he has done her<lb/>
                    by the present of a copy of<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#FrisL1">Professor Frisbie's</persName> writings<lb/>
                    and of his notice of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#FrisL1">Frisbie's</persName>
               <lb/>
                    life and works.<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>  The metaphysical <choice>
                  <orig>discus<lb/>
                    sions</orig>
                  <reg>discussions</reg>
               </choice> of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#FrisL1">Prof<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. F. </persName>appear to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Miss<lb/>
                        E</persName> to have great merit - <choice>
                  <orig>espe-<lb/>
                            cially</orig>
                  <reg>especially</reg>
               </choice> the remarks on <persName ref="./Personography.xml#SmitA1">Smiths</persName>
               <lb/>
               <title ref="./Workography.xml#Theor1">theory of moral sentiments</title>
               <lb/>
                    and those on Brown -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>  In the remarks on <persName ref="./Personography.xml#TaciP1">Tacitus</persName>
               <lb/>
                    Miss E was <hi rend="underline">astonished</hi> and<lb/>
               <hi rend="underline">gratified</hi>, and <hi rend="underline">ashamed</hi> to<lb/>
                    find her own name in such<lb/>
               <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Harvard_604760_1826-03_page02.jpg"/>
                    high company &amp; - mentioned<lb/>
                    in such terms - ! - She dares<lb/>
                    not say more lest she should<lb/>
               <del>be</del>
               <add>seem</add> immoderately vain or<lb/>
                    affectedly humble -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#NortA1">Professor Norton</persName> has given<lb/>
                    her great pleasure and<lb/>
                    she is sincerely grateful<lb/>
                    to him - <lb/>
            </p>
            <p>  She has desired her book<lb/>
                    seller to send him the <title ref="./Workography.xml#Janus1">
                  <choice>
                     <orig>Edin-<lb/>
                        burgh</orig>
                     <reg>Edinburgh</reg>
                  </choice> Literary Almanac</title> for<lb/>
                    this year in which there are<lb/>
                    some remarks on Brown<lb/>
                    &amp; other metaphysical Essays<lb/>
                    which perhaps may interest<lb/>
                    him - <lb/>
            </p>
            <p>  Some of the Essays are by<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LockJ1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Lockhart</persName>  one or two she<lb/>
               <hi rend="underline">guesses</hi> are by <persName ref="./Personography.xml#ScotW1">Sir Walter Scott</persName>
               <lb/>
               <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Harvard_604760_1826-03_page03.jpg"/>   
                    but this <hi rend="underline">last</hi> is only her <choice>
                  <orig>conjec<lb/>
                        ture</orig>
                  <reg>conjecture</reg>
               </choice> - of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LockJ1">Mr Lockhart's</persName> part she<lb/>
                    is certain as he told her <choice>
                  <orig>seve<lb/>
                        ral</orig>
                  <reg>several</reg>
               </choice> were his - </p>
            <p> If <persName ref="./Personography.xml#NortA1">Professor Norton</persName> or<lb/>
                    any of her friends should<lb/>
                    visit <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#IE">Ireland</placeName> Miss Edgworths<lb/>
                    family hope to have the <choice>
                  <orig>honer</orig>
                  <reg>honor</reg>
               </choice>
               <lb/>
                    of seeing them at <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Edgeworthstown_IE">Edgeworths<lb/>
                        Town</placeName>
               <lb/>
            </p>
            <closer>
               <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Edgeworthstown_IE">Edgeworths Town</placeName>
                    March 18<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>. 1826
                </closer>
            <postscript>
               <p>
                  <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Miss E</persName> hopes a <hi rend="underline">lady</hi> may
                        be excused for noticing the
                        beauty of the binding of
                        the vol sent to her -
                        <hi rend="underline">American</hi> binding is equal
                        to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#London_ENK">
                     <hi rend="underline">London</hi>
                  </placeName>
               </p>
            </postscript>
